{"title_page": "Citro\u00ebn XM", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = Citro\u00ebn XM\n| image = Citroen XM on a cliff top.jpg\n| manufacturer = [[Citro\u00ebn]] ([[PSA Group]])\n| production = 1989\u20132000<br />''333,405 built\n| designer = [[Gruppo Bertone|Bertone]]\n| class = [[Luxury vehicle#Mid-size luxury/executive cars|Mid-size luxury]] / [[Executive car]] ([[E-segment|E]])\n| body_style = 5-door [[hatchback]]<br/>5-door [[station wagon]]\n| related = [[Peugeot 605]]<ref name=\"citroenet.org.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.citroenet.org.uk/passenger-cars/psa/xm/xm-15.html|title=Citro\u00ebn XM|accessdate=28 November 2011|work=citroenet.org.uk}}</ref>\n| layout = [[FF layout]]\n| engine = [[PSA_XU_engine|2.0&nbsp;L XU10 I4]]<br/>[[PSA_XU_engine|2.0L XU10 I4]] [[Multi-valve|16 valve]]<br/>2.0L XU10 I4 [[Turbocharger|Turbocharged]]<br/>3.0L [[V6]] 12 valve<br/>[[V6_PRV_engine|3.0L PRV V6 24 valve]]<br/>[[V6_ESL_engine|2.9L ESL V6 24 valve]]<br/>[[PSA_XUD|2.1L XUD11 I4]] [[Diesel engine|Diesel]] 12 valve<br/>2.1L XUD11 I4 [[Turbodiesel]] 12 valve<br/>2.5L DK5 I4 Turbodiesel 12 valve\n| wheelbase = hatchback:{{convert|2850|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br/>station wagon:{{convert|2850|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = hatchback:{{convert|4708|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br/>station wagon:{{convert|4963|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br/>1998\u20132000 station wagon: {{convert|4950|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = hatchback:{{convert|1793|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}<br/>station wagon:{{convert|1794|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1392|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (most Berline models); some turbo models {{convert|1385|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}; {{convert|1466|mm|in|1|abbr=on}} (1998 V6 Break)\n| weight = {{convert|1310|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}-{{convert|1550|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}}\n| predecessor = [[Citro\u00ebn CX]]\n| successor = [[Citro\u00ebn C6]]<br>[[Citro\u00ebn C5]]<ref>[http://www.lesechos.fr/20/10/2000/LesEchos/18262-520-ECH_citroen-c5---banale---deesse----.htm Les \u00e9chos, 20/10/2000]</ref><ref>[http://www.autodeclics.com/citroen/essai/14-essai_citroen_c5_c5_20_hdi_110_sx.html Auto d\u00e9clics]</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Citro\u00ebn XM''' is an [[executive car]] that was produced by the French [[automaker]] [[Citro\u00ebn]] between 1989 and 2000. Citro\u00ebn sold 333,775 XMs during the model's 11 years of production. The XM was voted 1990 [[European Car of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/motoring/4758195/Portrait-of-a-driver-Jonathan-Meades.html | location=London | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Harry | last=Mount | title=Portrait of a driver: Jonathan Meades | date=22 February 2003}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nLaunched on 23 May 1989,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/03/22/business/company-news-new-citroen-model-offered-by-peugeot.html?scp=4&sq=Citroen%20xm&st=cse |title=COMPANY NEWS; New Citroen Model Offered by Peugeot \u2013 New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=22 March 1989 |accessdate=22 December 2011}}</ref> the XM was the modern iteration of the ''Big Citro\u00ebn'', a flagship saloon replacement for the [[Citro\u00ebn CX]]. It went on sale in its native [[France]] immediately afterwards, and was available in right-hand drive on the UK market from October 1989.\n\nThe XM estate was launched in the spring of 1991, until which time the estate version of the CX remained in production.\n\nThe XM inherited a loyal global customer base of executive class customers and a clear [[Brand#Corporate Brand Identity|brand image]], but did not enjoy the commercial success and iconic status of its predecessors, the [[Citro\u00ebn CX|CX]] and the [[Citro\u00ebn DS|DS]], which both raised the bar of automotive performance for other manufacturers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nekrolog: Den store Citro\u00ebn er d\u00f8d|first=Claus|last=Ebberfeld|url=http://www.viaretro.com/2012/12/nekrolog-den-store-citroen-er-dod/|archive-url=https://archive.today/20141121082409/http://www.viaretro.com/2012/12/nekrolog-den-store-citroen-er-dod/|url-status=dead|archive-date=21 November 2014|date=20 December 2012|accessdate=21 November 2014}} In Danish</ref>\n\nWith total sales over its lifetime of just 330,000 units in 11 years, and the fact that its replacement [[Citro\u00ebn C6]] was not launched until the end of 2005 (despite being scheduled for launch in 2001), the XM might be considered a failure. By the second half of the 1990s, sales were in sharp decline, but Citro\u00ebn did not end production of the car until 2000.\n\nDespite its common roots with the Peugeot 605, the XM is already emerging as a collectible car, as the DS and CX both did.<ref name=\"Classic pp 144-151\"/>\n\n===Advances in Design===\nThere were many advances, most apparently designed to counteract the main criticisms of its predecessor. The CX leaned in corners, so the XM had active electronic management of the suspension; the CX rusted, so the XM had a partially galvanised body shell (many surviving XMs have very little corrosion); the CX was underpowered, so the XM offered the option of a 3.0&nbsp;L [[V6]] engine&nbsp;\u2013&nbsp;the first V6 in a Citro\u00ebn since the [[Maserati]]-engined [[Citro\u00ebn SM|SM]] ceased production in the mid 1970s. When the estate model joined the line-up, Citro\u00ebn had a competitor at almost every level with most other similar-sized European cars.\n\nVentilation was markedly more effective in the XM. Rear accommodation in the XM was improved over the CX in both width, legroom and height. In particular the rear passengers were seated higher than those in the front in order to afford a good view out, important for a vehicle which would operate in French government service.<ref>The Daily Express World Car Guide 1998, page 30</ref> The XM shared a floorpan with the [[Peugeot 605]], and the two models fared similarly in both teething problems and market acceptance.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} Unlike the 605 [[Sedan (automobile)|sedan]] design, the XM was a [[liftback]] design&nbsp;-&nbsp;a feature thought to be desirable in certain European markets - perhaps uniquely, it featured an additional glass panel that could lift with the tailgate but when shut, isolated the passenger compartment, to mimic the feel of a salon car.\n\n===Competition===\nXM was intended to compete against prestige vehicles like the [[Audi 100]] and [[BMW 5 Series|BMW's 5 Series]] in a sector that accounted for 14.2% of the European market. It also competed with cars from mainstream brands including the [[Ford Scorpio]] and [[Opel Omega]]. Citro\u00ebn was quoted as saying that the car was supposed to \"take what Citro\u00ebn means and make it acceptable\".<ref name=\"autocar38\">Autocar, 24 May 1989, page 38.</ref> The car's initial reception was positive. Some six months after its launch, The XM won the prestigious [[European Car of the Year]] award for 1990 (gaining almost twice as many votes as the second, the [[Mercedes-Benz SL]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.caroftheyear.org/previous-winners/1990_1/coty |title=Previous winners |publisher=Car of the year |accessdate=18 September 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130626071657/http://www.caroftheyear.org/previous-winners/1990_1/coty |archive-date=26 June 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and went on to win a further 14 major awards within a year of its launch.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.piecescitroensport.citroen.com/CWW/en-US/HISTORY/CITROENHISTORY/1990TO1999/ |title=Citro\u00ebn in 1990 |publisher=Piecescitroensport.citroen.com |date= |accessdate=7 August 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111008130824/http://www.piecescitroensport.citroen.com/CWW/en-US/HISTORY/CITROENHISTORY/1990TO1999/ |archive-date=8 October 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe anticipated annual sales of 450 cars a day in the first full year of production, or 160,000 units a year, never materialized.<ref>Car Styling, July 1989, page 7.</ref> Sales never reached this ambitious level (higher than even its popular predecessor) for a variety of reasons. Like the CX, the XM did not have the worldwide distribution of competitors from [[BMW]], [[Audi]], and [[Mercedes-Benz]]. Also, it was launched only a year before a [[Early 1990s recession|major global recession]] began, impacting negatively on car sales across the world; a notable example being the UK, where more than 2.3 million new cars were registered in 1989, but that figure fell to less than 1.6 million in 1991 (a drop of more than 30% in just two years). In Japan the XM was sold through [[Mazda]]'s [[Eunos (automobile)|Eunos]] dealership chain, part of an effort to minimize the appearance of Japan's automobile market being closed to imports.<ref name=DaiRede>{{citation | title = Daihatsu Automobile: Erfahrung f\u00fcr die Zukunft | last = Kie\u00dfler | first = Bernd-Wilfried | language = de | ref = DAK | page = 52 | isbn = 9783517012254 | publisher = S\u00fcdwest | date = 1992 }}</ref> It was also offered by Citro\u00ebn's traditional importer [[Seibu Department Stores|Seibu Motor]], who kept selling the XM by themselves after the Eunos brand was discontinued in 1996.\n\nThe market for executive cars made by volume manufacturers ([[Ford]], [[Opel]], etc.) was on the verge of decline as customers opted for offerings from more prestigious marques, a trend which saw Ford pull out of this market sector in 1998<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ford_Scorpio</ref> and Opel in 2003.<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opel_Omega</ref> Customers were placing a higher priority on speed and handling rather than ride comfort which was Citro\u00ebn's specialty.{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} The XM was underdeveloped at launch which resulted in reliability problems; the vehicle as designed was inconsistent in its abilities. The XM's styling was also controversial and alienated those who desired a more conventional [[Sedan (automobile)|three box sedan]].{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} Peugeot introduced an XM competitor, the very similar [[Peugeot 605]] that also sold weakly. Most subjective of all was the matter of the XM not living up to the expectations created by its forerunner the [[Citro\u00ebn DS]],{{citation needed|date=April 2012}} despite that car having been launched in an era of national markets, of different demands and standards, an era when there was more scope for large advances in engineering and design than were possible in 1989.\n\nExport markets experienced lower sales from the outset, partly due to the XM's pricing. The least expensive XM was nearly 50% more expensive at the time of launch than the corresponding CX. Whilst strong at first<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1991/07/01/business/market-place-slumping-peugeot-is-recommended.html?scp=2&sq=Citroen%20xm&st=cse |title=Market Place; Slumping Peugeot Is Recommended \u2013 New York Times |publisher=Nytimes.com |date=1 July 1991 |accessdate=22 December 2011 |first=Steven |last=Greenhouse}}</ref> home market sales also declined, after the mechanical issues of the first few model years became known. \n\nBy early 1993, the XM was viewed as an \"underachiever\".<ref name=\"Autocar, 24 Feb, page 54\">[Autocar, 24 Feb, page 54].</ref> Initial sales in the UK were at 3,500 units a year, making it Citro\u00ebn's weakest seller. The 2.0-litre petrol engined variants were viewed as being the least competitive. As a result, Citro\u00ebn restructured the range such that all but the base model petrols were fitted with low-inertia Garret turbochargers to add an extra {{convert|15|bhp|kW|0|abbr=on}}. This made the cars more powerful than more expensive competitors such as the Rover 820, Vauxhall Carlton and Ford Granada 2.0 GLX.<ref name=\"Autocar, 24 Feb, page 54\"/>\n\nAfter a run of 11 years, production finally ended in June 2000. By 1998, Citro\u00ebn had confirmed that it would soon be discontinuing the XM and replacing it with an all-new model. At the Geneva Motor Show in March 1999, it unveiled the C6 Lignage concept car, which was scheduled for launch in 2001. In the event, the XM's successor - the C6 - did not go on sale until late 2005 and was even less successful.<ref>{{cite web|first=Julian|last=Marsh |url=http://www.citroenet.org.uk/passenger-cars/psa/xm/xm-index.html |title=Citro\u00ebn XM |publisher=Citroenet.org.uk |date=10 June 2000 |accessdate=7 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Facelift===\nIn mid-1994, the XM was revised in order to improve competitiveness.<ref name=\"Car, May 1995 p94-104\">Car, May 1995 p94-104</ref> This did not materially impact sales.\n\nAll models were fitted with driver's airbag (signalling the end of the single-spoke steering wheel), belt-pretensioners, a redesigned dashboard and upper door casings. The suspension was redesigned to reduce roll, pitch and dive. Most noticeable was the adoption of a passive rear-steering system similar to that on the [[Citro\u00ebn Xantia]]. This sharpened the \"steering without inducing a nervous twitch.<ref name=\"Car, May 1995 p94-104\"/>\" Power output on the turbocharged motor was increased to {{convert|150|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} from {{convert|145|bhp|kW PS|0|abbr=on}} at 4400 rpm. This allowed the car to develop more torque at much lower revs. The important 50\u201370 acceleration time was 8 seconds compared to the [[Ford Scorpio]] 2.0 16V Ghia's 17 seconds. The view of ''[[Car (magazine)|CAR]]'' magazine was that this engine \"provides unusually swift access to effortless power ... it delivers progressively with commendably little fuss; that this 2.0 turbo is as refined as it is muscular makes the XM's performance all the more creditable<ref name=\"Car, May 1995 p94-104\"/>\".\n\nIn the [[United Kingdom]] market, demand was reduced to a virtual trickle by the late 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|author=Custom byline text:&nbsp; Ross Finlay |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/seduced-by-gallic-charmers-1.253952 |title=Accessed Dec 21, 2011 |publisher=Heraldscotland.com |date=14 January 2000 |accessdate=22 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Custom byline text:&nbsp; ROSS FINLAY |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/sport/spl/aberdeen/prestige-and-performance-round-up-1.342854 |title=Prestige and performance round-up |publisher=Herald Scotland |date=21 May 1998 |accessdate=22 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Style==\n{{Multiple image | align = left | direction = vertical | width =\n| image1 = 1993 Citro\u00ebn XM hatchback (28603668230).jpg\n| image2 = 1993 citroen xm us model rear sidemarker light.jpg\n| caption2 = Hatchback (pre-facelift)\n| image3 = Citroen XM Break (1991-1994) II.jpg\n| caption3 = Break (pre-facelift)\n}}\n{{Multiple image | align = right | direction = vertical | width =\n| image1 = 2000 Citro\u00ebn XM hatchback (2010-11-28).jpg\n| caption1 = Hatchback (facelift)\n| image2 = Citroen XM Safari long time resident.JPG\n| caption2 = Break (facelift)\n| image3 = 1995 Citroen XM Break VSX Turbo 2.0 Rear.jpg\n| caption3 = Break (facelift)\n}}\n\nThe angular, dart-like [[Gruppo Bertone|Bertone]] design was a development of [[Marcello Gandini]]'s [[Citro\u00ebn BX]] concept. It was a longer car with a longer, inclined nose, more refined details and with headlamps that were very much slimmer than the norm (Gandini's own XM proposal was rejected as looking too much like an Opel<ref>CAR, June 1989</ref>). The design process of the car was described in the journal ''Car Styling''.<ref>Car Styling, 1989,7., pp 6\u201316</ref> In the article Citro\u00ebn's design chief, Art Blakeslee, explained the appearance of the car, saying \"I believe the XM is a modern and dynamic shape, with unique styling elements such as the very long, low hood, the extensive use of glass and the kick-up in the belt line\". In the book ''Citroen XM''<ref>\"Citroen XM\" Jan P. Norbye, Autmobilia, Italy, 1989. Page 62.</ref> another Citro\u00ebn designer, Daniel Abramson, explained: \"We lowered the belt line to give the shape a stronger image. It is purely a 'design statement' that is not functional and does nothing for the aerodynamics of the vehicle. We wanted a car that looks good from every angle\". Abramson is also reported as saying that they \"picked three areas to emphasise: 1) A very aggressive look (\"Almost sinister\"), 2) Lots of glass to create a greenhouse effect, and 3) An aerodynamic accent based on fact (low drag)<ref>\"Citroen XM\" Jan P. Norbye, Autmobilia, Italy, 1989. Page 63</ref>\".\n\nDesign critic Jonathan Meades described the XM as the last gothic car, as quoted by [[Stephen Bayley]] in \"Design Made Visible\" (2007).<ref>Stephen Bayley, Terence Conran. 2007 \u201cDesign: intelligence made visible\u201d. Firefly Books, 2007. Page 115</ref> In 2013 ''Car''<ref>Bird, G. (2013) \"Bertone at 100\" Car, April 2013, page 115.</ref> magazine described the XM as one of Bertone's seven \"game changer\" designs, referring to its \"cool\" angular design and its \"distinctive staggered beltline\".\n{{clear}}\n\n==Suspension==\n[[File:Citroen XM-Rear.jpg|thumb|left|1994\u20132000 Citro\u00ebn XM (suspension fully lowered)]]\nThe [[hydropneumatic]] [[self-leveling suspension]] (featuring grapefruit-sized metal spheres containing [[nitrogen]], acting as both springs and shock absorbers) gained a very sophisticated electronic control system called [[Hydractive]]. This system used sensors in the steering, brakes, suspension, throttle pedal and transmission to feed information on the car's speed, acceleration, and road conditions to on-board computers. Where appropriate \u2013 and within milliseconds \u2013 these computers switched an extra suspension sphere in or out of circuit, to allow the car a [[ride quality|smooth supple ride]] in normal circumstances, or greater roll resistance for better handling in corners.\n\nThe Hydractive system was somewhat \"ahead of the curve\" when the car was launched and early versions were sometimes unreliable. Many problems stemmed from the sensitive electronics controlling the car's hydraulic system, often caused by the poor quality of the multipoint grounding blocks \u2013 one on each front inner wing, one at the rear, and one under the dashboard. These tended to corrode (especially the ones in the engine compartment), causing all manner of intermittent faults which were hard to diagnose. On later cars, these were changed to screw terminals bolted through the bodywork, and most of the older cars have been modified in a similar way.\n\nWhen the Hydractive system worked, the result was a big car with a smooth \"magic carpet\" ride, and better handling than many smaller, lighter, sports cars. When it didn't work, it was quite harsh and bumpy, although no worse than any contemporary high-performance sports sedan. However, right-hand drive XMs were never fitted with the [[DIRAVI]] variable fully powered steering of the CX, having an almost conventional [[DIRASS]] power-assisted setup.\n\nAlthough the Hydractive suspension coped superbly with undulations and driving at speed, it could be unexpectedly harsh if a sudden change in road height was encountered at moderate speed - eg lateral ridges or speed bumps.  Citro\u00ebn finally addressed this, and for Xantia (which shared the Hydractive system with XM) came up with a modified design of the suspension (centre sphere) regulator valves, which made them immune to hydraulic impulses produced by the road surface, and which could push the older-type valves into Firm mode, just when this wasn't needed.  The modified valves were fitted to production Xantias from 8 March 1999 (and were available as replacements), but were not fitted to XM, which was nearing end of production.  Interest in these new-type valves has led to a good few XM owners successfully fitting them, and benefiting from a noticeable improvement in smoothness and consistency of ride.\n\nSome production models of the XM were not equipped with the Hydractive system, but had a 'conventional' [[hydropneumatic]] suspension closer to that of the [[Citro\u00ebn BX]]. These lower specification vehicles were all built for markets in mainland Europe.\n\n==Engines==\nThe XM was fitted with a wide range of gasoline and diesel engines:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:91%;\"\n|-\n!Model!!Engine!!Displacement!!Valvetrain!!Fuel system!!Max. power at rpm!!Max. torque at rpm!!0\u2013100&nbsp;km/h (0-62 mph)!!Top speed!!Years\n|-\n| colspan=\"10\" |Petrol engines\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''2.0'''||[[PSA XU engine#XU10|XU10 2C]]||1,998 cc||[[Single overhead camshaft|SOHC]] 8v||[[Carburettor]]||{{convert|114|PS|kW hp||abbr=on}} at 5,800 rpm||{{convert|164|Nm|lbft||abbr=on}} at 2,250 rpm||12.2 s||{{convert|193|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}||1989\u20131992\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''2.0 [[catalytic converter|cat]]'''||[[PSA XU engine#XU10|XU10 2C]]||1,998 cc||[[Single overhead camshaft|SOHC]] 8v||[[Carburettor]]||{{convert|107|PS|kW hp||abbr=on}} at 5,600 rpm||{{convert|164|Nm|lbft||abbr=on}} at 2,250 rpm||12.4 s||{{convert|190|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}||1989\u20131992\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''2.0 i [[catalytic converter|cat]]'''||[[PSA XU engine#XU10|XU10]]||1,998 cc||[[Single overhead camshaft|SOHC]] 8v||[[Single-point fuel injection]]||{{convert|110|PS|kW hp|0|abbr=on}} at 5,600 rpm||{{convert|164|Nm|lbft||abbr=on}} at 3,500 rpm||12.4 s||{{convert|190|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}||1989\u20131994\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''2.0 i'''||[[PSA XU engine#XU10|XU10]] M||1,998 cc||[[Single overhead camshaft|SOHC]] 8v||[[Multi-point fuel injection]]||{{convert|128|PS|kW hp||abbr=on}} at 5,600 rpm||{{convert|175|Nm|lbft||abbr=on}} at 4,800 rpm||11.5 s||{{convert|205|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}||1989\u20131992\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|'''2.0 i [[catalytic converter|cat]]'''||[[PSA XU engine#XU10|XU10]] J2C (RFU)||1,998 cc||[[Single overhead camshaft|SOHC]] 8v||[[Multi-point fuel injection]]||{{convert|121|PS|kW hp||abbr=on}} at 5,600 rpm||{{convert|170|Nm|lbft|0|abbr=on}} at 4,000 rpm||11.9 s||{{convert|201|km/h|mi/h|0|abbr=on}}||1