{"title_page": "Snow Hill, Maryland", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Snow Hill, Maryland\n|settlement_type          = [[Town]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Snow Hill business center (2008).jpg\n|imagesize                = 220px\n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map = Worcester_County_Maryland_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Snow_Hill_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location in Worcester County and the state of Maryland\n| pushpin_map             = Maryland#USA\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_label           = Snow Hill\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location within the state of Maryland\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Maryland]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Maryland|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Worcester County, Maryland|Worcester]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Gary Weber\n|leader_title1            = [[Town Council]]\n|leader_name1             = {{Collapsible list\n|title       = Member List\n|frame_style=border:none; padding: 0; <!--NOTICE: This will hide the borders and make rows closer (padding)-->\n|title_style = \n|list_style  = text-align:left;display:none; <!-- NOTICE: This will always collapse the list-->\n|1= Jenny Hall\n|2=Alison Cook\n|3=LaToya Purnell\n}}\n|established_title        = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date         = 1812<ref>{{cite web|title=Snow Hill|url=http://msa.maryland.gov/msa/mdmanual/37mun/snow/html/s.html|website=Maryland Manual|accessdate=28 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_24.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jan 2, 2019}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 8.14\n|area_land_km2            = 7.85\n|area_water_km2           = 0.29\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 3.14\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 3.03\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.11\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 2038\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\"/>\n|population_total         = 2103\n|population_density_km2   = 261.42\n|population_density_sq_mi = 677.00\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 5\n|elevation_ft             = 16\n|coordinates              = {{coord|38|10|30|N|75|23|27|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 21863\n|area_code                = [[Area code 410|410]], [[Area code 443|443]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 24-73075\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0587416\n|website                  = [http://www.snowhillmd.com/ www.snowhillmd.com]\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n}}\n'''Snow Hill''' is a town in and the [[county seat]] of [[Worcester County, Maryland|Worcester County]], [[Maryland]], United States.<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=2011-06-07|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref> The population was 2,103 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. It is part of the [[Salisbury metropolitan area|Salisbury, Maryland-Delaware Metropolitan Statistical Area]].\n\n==History==\nSnow Hill was founded in 1686 in [[Somerset County, Maryland|Somerset County]] by [[England|English]] settlers, who may have named it after a street and neighborhood of the [[City of London]] called \"[[Snow Hill, London|Snow Hill]]\", despite the location's elevation of just {{convert|16|ft}} above sea level and the infrequency of snowfall. The town received its first charter on October 26, 1686, and was made a port of entry in 1694.{{citation needed|date = November 2019}}\n\nIn 1742, [[Worcester County, Maryland|Worcester County]] was carved out of the eastern half of old [[Somerset County, Maryland|Somerset County]] and Snow Hill, centrally located in the new county and at the head of navigation on the [[Pocomoke River]], was made the [[County seat|county seat]].{{citation needed|date = November 2019}}\n\nMajor fires in 1844 and 1893 destroyed the center of Snow Hill, including two successive [[Courthouse|Court Houses]], although some eighteenth century structures survived both fires. Following the second fire, much of the commercial area was rapidly rebuilt, so the downtown today contains many historic buildings of the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries.  The Snow Hill [[Historic district (United States)#Local-level|Historic District]], which includes approximately 80% of the town, was created in 2002.{{citation needed|date = November 2019}}\n\nIn December 2010, a Snow Hill businessman started a petition to remove the town's incorporation and revert the area to county control. The reasons given were lower county taxes, better services provided to the town, and a need for revitalization. The push was abandoned in January 2011.<ref>http://www.wboc.com/Global/story.asp?S=13935194</ref>\n\nThe [[All Hallows Episcopal Church]], [[Chanceford]], [[Old Friendship United Methodist Church]], [[Samuel Gunn House]], [[Makemie Memorial Presbyterian Church]], [[James Martin House (Snow Hill, Maryland)|James Martin House]], [[Nassawango Iron Furnace Site]], [[Nun's Green]], [[George Washington Purnell House]], and [[Gov. John Walter Smith House]] are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nSnow Hill is located at {{coord|38|10|30|N|75|23|27|W|type:city}} (38.175024, -75.390738).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the town has a total area of {{convert|3.12|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|3.01|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.11|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2013-01-25|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125061959/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|archivedate=2012-01-25}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1850= 714\n|1860= 966\n|1870= 960\n|1880= 1276\n|1890= 1483\n|1900= 1596\n|1910= 1844\n|1920= 1684\n|1930= 1604\n|1940= 1926\n|1950= 2091\n|1960= 2311\n|1970= 2201\n|1980= 2192\n|1990= 2217\n|2000= 2409\n|2010= 2103\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=2038\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\">{{cite web|title=U.S. Census website|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2013-01-25}}</ref> of 2010, there were 2,103 people, 871 households, and 557 families residing in the town. The [[population density]] was {{convert|698.7|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 1,005 housing units at an average density of {{convert|333.9|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the town was 57.0% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 39.0% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.2% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1.3% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.3% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 2.2% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.6% of the population.\n\nThere were 871 households of which 31.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 36.7% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 21.9% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.3% had a male householder with no wife present, and 36.1% were non-families. 32.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 16% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.32 and the average family size was 2.90.\n\nThe median age in the town was 44.7 years. 23.2% of residents were under the age of 18; 7.9% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 19.3% were from 25 to 44; 29.4% were from 45 to 64; and 20.2% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the town was 45.9% male and 54.1% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 2,409 people, 862 households, and 555 families residing in the town. The [[population density]] was 1,806.2 people per square mile (699.3/km\u00b2). There were 964 housing units at an average density of 722.8 per square mile (279.9/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the town was 56.00% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 42.34% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.08% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.58% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.04% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.37% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.58% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.08% of the population.\n\nThere were 862 households out of which 28.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 40.6% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 20.2% had a female householder with no husband present, and 35.5% were non-families. 31.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 15.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.37 and the average family size was 2.94.\n\nIn the town, the population was spread out with 21.0% under the age of 18, 9.3% from 18 to 24, 29.6% from 25 to 44, 20.5% from 45 to 64, and 19.5% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 39 years. For every 100 females, there were 99.4 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 95.5 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the town was $29,730, and the median income for a family was $38,657. Males had a median income of $25,439 versus $20,625 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the town was $15,560. About 14.8% of families and 15.9% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 19.5% of those under age 18 and 13.1% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Worcester County Courthouse.jpg|thumb|Worcester County Courthouse in Snow Hill.]]\nSnow Hill is the location of:\n\n* Snow Hill Elementary School\n* Snow Hill Middle School\n* [[Snow Hill High School]]\n* Cedar Chapel Special School\n\n==Religion==\n{{Expand section|Other Religions|date=June 2017}}\nA number of [[Protestant]] religious denominations have churches in Snow Hill; several are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]]:\n\n* [[All Hallows Episcopal Church]]\n* [[Makemie Memorial Presbyterian Church]]\n* Bates Memorial United Methodist Church\n* [[Richard Whatcoat|Whatcoat]] United Methodist Church\n* Ebenezer United Methodist Church\n* Snow Hill Christian Church\n* Old School Baptist Church\n* Mt. Zion Baptist Church\n* Hutt's Memorial United Methodist Church\n\n==Notable people==\n{{More citations needed section|date=June 2017}}\n* [[Arch Johnson]], stage, film, and television actor died in Snow Hill in 1997.\n* [[Judy Johnson]], was a player in the Negro Baseball Leagues and later a scout in the major leagues.  In 1975, Johnson was inducted into the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]].  He was born William Julius \"Judy\" Johnson in Snow Hill on October 26, 1900.\n* [[Sherron Mills]], professional basketball player, 1971-2016\n* [[John Walter Smith]], Congressman for [[Maryland's 1st congressional district|Maryland 1st District]], 1899\u20131900; 44th Governor of Maryland, 1900\u20131904; U.S. Senator, 1907-1919.  Born in Snow Hill on Feb 5, 1845.\n* [[Ben Tate]], NFL running back,who attended Snow Hill HS during his senior year in 2006; led team to the Maryland state championship game.\n* [[R. V. Truitt]], first lacrosse coach at the [[University of Maryland]], 1919&ndash;1927.  Founder of the Chesapeake Biological Laboratory in Solomons, MD (1925), now part of the [[University of Maryland Center for Environmental Science]].  World renkown marine ecologist who studied blue crab and oyster.\n* [[Ephraim King Wilson II]], U.S. Senator, 1885\u20131891; Congressman for [[United States House of Representatives, Maryland District 1|Maryland 1st District]], 1873-1874.  Born in Snow Hill on December 22, 1821.\n\n==Snow Hill in popular culture==\nIn 1999, some scenes of the [[Hollywood]] film, ''[[Runaway Bride (film)|Runaway Bride]]'' (starring [[Julia Roberts]] and [[Richard Gere]]) were shot at the [[Snow Hill High School]]. The scenes at the baseball and football games were filmed behind the school.\n\nAt the end of each episode of Adult Swim's \"Children Hospital,\" is an old advertisement for The Corddry Co Snow Hill, MD.  Seen after the final credits.  The lead actor, writer, and producer is comedian Rob Corddry, whose father is from Snow Hill. He uses the advertisement as his  production banner.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Julia A. Purnell Museum]]\n* [[Furnace Town Living Heritage Museum]]\n* [[Mt. Zion One Room School]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Snow Hill}}\n* [http://www.snowhillmd.com/ Town of Snow Hill website]\n\n{{Geographic Location 2\n | Center    = Snow Hill\n | North     = [[Bowie, Maryland|Bowie]]<br/>[[File:US 301.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Route 301 in Maryland|US 301 North]] \n | Northeast = [[Berlin, Maryland|Berlin]]<br/>[[File:US 113.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Route 113 in Maryland|US 301 South]]\n | East      = Snow Hill Wharf<br/>[[File:MD Route 258.svg|25px]] [[Maryland Route 365|MD 365 East]]\n | ENE       = \n | Southeast = [[Chincoteague Bay]]\n | Southwest = [[Pocomoke City, Maryland|Pocomoke City]]<br/>[[File:US 113.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Route 113 in Maryland|US 301 South]]\n | South     = [[Stockton, Maryland|Stockton]], [[Chincoteague, Virginia]]<br/>[[File:MD Route 12.svg|25px]] [[Maryland Route 12|MD 12 South]]\n | WSW       =\n | West      = [[Pocomoke State Forest]]\n | WNW       =\n | Northwest = [[Salisbury, Maryland|Salisbury]]<br/>[[File:MD Route 12.svg|25px]] [[Maryland Route 12|MD 12 North]]\n}}\n\n{{Maryland}}\n{{Worcester County, Maryland}}\n{{County Seats of Maryland}}\n{{Salisbury metropolitan area}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:English-American culture in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Towns in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Towns in Worcester County, Maryland]]\n[[Category:County seats in Maryland]]\n[[Category:1686 establishments in Maryland]]\n[[Category:Salisbury metropolitan area]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Snow Hill, Maryland\n|settlement_type          = [[Town]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = Snow Hill business center (2008).jpg\n|imagesize                = 220px\n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map = Worcester_County_Maryland_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Snow_Hill_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250px\n|map_caption              = Location in Worcester County and the state of Maryland\n| pushpin_map             = Maryland#USA\n| pushpin_label_position  = \n| pushpin_label           = Snow Hill\n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location within the state of Maryland\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Maryland]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Maryland|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Worcester County, Maryland|Worcester]]\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = [[Mayor]]\n|leader_name              = Gary Weber\n|leader_title1            = [[Town Council]]\n|leader_name1             = {{Collapsible list\n|title       = Member List\n|frame_style=border:none; padding: 0; <!--NOTICE: This will hide the borders and make rows closer (padding)-->\n|title_style = \n|list_style  = text-align:left;display:none; <!-- NOTICE: This will always collapse the list-->\n|1= Jenny Hall\n|2=Alison Cook\n|3=LaToya Purnell\n}}\n|established_title        = [[Municipal corporation|Incorporated]]\n|established_date         = 1812<ref>{{cite web|title=Snow Hill|url=http://msa.maryland.gov/msa/mdmanual/37mun/snow/html/s.html|website=Maryland Manual|accessdate=28 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|unit_pref                = Imperial\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_24.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jan 2, 2019}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 8.14\n|area_land_km2            = 7.85\n|area_water_km2           = 0.29\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 3.14\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 3.03\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.11\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 2038\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\"/>\n|population_total         = 2103\n|population_density_km2   = 261.42\n|population_density_sq_mi = 677.00\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 5\n|elevation_ft             = 16\n|coordinates              = {{coord|38|10|30|N|75|23|27|W|region:US_type:city|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 21863\n|area_code                = [[Area code 410|410]], [[Area code 443|443]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 24-73075\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0587416\n|website                  = [http://www.snowhillmd.com/ www.snowhillmd.com]\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n}}\n'''Snow Hill''' is a town in and the [[county seat]] of [[Worcester County, Maryland|Worcester County]], [[Maryland]], United States.<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=2011-06-07|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref> The population was 2,103 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. It is part of the [[Salisbury metropolitan area|Salisbury, Maryland-Delaware Metropolitan Statistical Area]].\n\n==History==\nSnow Hill was founded in 1686 in [[Somerset County, Maryland|Somerset County]] by [[England|English]] settlers, who may have named it after a street and neighborhood of the [[City of London]] called \"[[Snow Hill, London|Snow Hill]]\", despite the location's elevation of just {{convert|16|ft}} above sea level and the infrequency of snowfall. The town received its first charter on October 26, 1686, and was made a port of entry in 1694.{{citation needed|date = November 2019}}\n\nIn 1742, [[Worcester County, Maryland|Worcester County]] was carved out of the eastern half of old [[Somerset County, Maryland|Somerset County]] and Snow Hill, centrally located in the new county and at the head of navigation on the [[Pocomoke River]], was made the [[County seat|county seat]].{{citation needed|date = November 2019}}\n\nMajor fires in 1844 and 1893 destroyed the center of Snow Hill, including two successive [[Courthouse|Court Houses]], although some eighteenth century structures survived both fires. Following the second fire, much of the commercial area was rapidly rebuilt, so the downtown today contains many historic buildings of the late nineteenth and early twentieth centuries.  The Snow Hill [[Historic district (United States)#Local-level|Historic District]], which includes approximately 80% of the town, was created in 2002.{{citation needed|date = November 2019}}\n\nIn December 2010, a Snow Hill businessman started a petition to remove the town's incorporation and revert the area to county control. The reasons given were lower county taxes, better services provided to the town, and a need for revitalization. The push was abandoned in January 2011.<ref>http://www.wboc.com/Global/story.asp?S=13935194</ref>\n\nThe [[All Hallows Episcopal Church]], [[Chanceford]], [[Old Friendship United Methodist Church]], [[Samuel Gunn House]], [[Makemie Memorial Presbyterian Church]], [[James Martin House (Snow Hill, Maryland)|James Martin House]], [[Nassawango Iron Furnace Site]], [[Nun's Green]], [[George Washington Purnell House]], and [[Gov. John Walter Smith House]] are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nSnow Hill is located at {{coord|38|10|30|N|75|23|27|W|type:city}} (38.175024, -75.390738).<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geographies/reference-files/time-series/geo/gazetteer-files.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the town has a total area of {{convert|3.12|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|3.01|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.11|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2013-01-25|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125061959/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|archivedate=2012-01-25}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1850= 714\n|1860= 966\n|1870= 960\n|1880= 1276\n|1890= 1483\n|1900= 1596\n|1910= 1844\n|1920= 1684\n|1930= 1604\n|1940= 1926\n|1950= 2091\n|1960= 2311\n|1970= 2201\n|1980= 2192\n|1990= 2217\n|2000= 2409\n|2010= 2103\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=2038\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=December 21, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/decennial-census.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"wwwcensusgov\">{{cite web|title=U.S. Census website|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2013-01-25}}</ref> of 2010, there were 2,103 people, 871 households, and 557 families residing in the town. The [[population density]] was {{convert|698.7|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 1,005 housing units at an average density of {{convert|333.9|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the town was 57.0% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 39.0% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.2% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 1.3% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.3% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 2.2% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.6% of the population.\n\nThere were 871 households of which 31.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 36.7% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 21.9% had a female householder with no husband present, 5.3% had a male householder with no wife present, and 36.1% were non-families. 32.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 16% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.32 and the average family size was 2.90.\n\nThe median age in the town was 44.7 years. 23.2% of residents were under the age of 18; 7.9% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 19.3% were from 25 to 44; 29.4% were from 45 to 64; and 20.2% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the town was 45.9% male and 54.1% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=U.S. Census website}}</ref> of 2000, there were 2,409 people, 862 households, and 555 families residing in the town. The [[population density]] was 1,806.2 people per square mile (699.3/km\u00b2). There were 964 housing units at an average density of 722.8 per square mile (279.9/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the town was 56.00% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 42.34% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.08% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.58% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.04% [[Pacific Islander (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.37% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.58% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.08% of the population.\n\nThere were 862 households out of which 28.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 40.6% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 20.2% had a female householder with no husband present, and 35.5% were non-families. 31.4% of all households were made up of individuals and 15.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.37 and the average family size was 2.94.\n\nIn the town, the population was spread out with 21.0% under the age of 18, 9.3% from 18 to 24, 29.6% from 25 to 44, 20.5% from 45 to 64, and 19.5% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 39 years. For every 100 females, there were 99.4 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 95.5 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the town was $29,730, and the median income for a family was $38,657. Males had a median income of $25,439 versus $20,625 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the town was $15,560. About 14.8% of families and 15.9% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 19.5% of those under age 18 and 13.1% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Worcester County Courthouse.jpg|thumb|Worcester County Courthouse in Snow Hill.]]\nSnow Hill is the location of:\n\n* Snow Hill Elementary School\n* Snow Hill Middle School\n* [[Snow Hill High School]]\n* Cedar Chapel Special School\n\n==Religion==\n{{Expand section|Other Religions|date=June 2017}}\nA number of [[Protestant]] religious denominations have churches in Snow Hill; several are listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]]:\n\n* [[All Hallows Episcopal Church]]\n* [[Makemie Memorial Presbyterian Church]]\n* Bates Memorial United Methodist Church\n* [[Richard Whatcoat|Whatcoat]] United Methodist Church\n* Ebenezer United Methodist Church\n* Snow Hill Christian Church\n* Old School Baptist Church\n* Mt. Zion Baptist Church\n* Hutt's Memorial United Methodist Church\n\n==Notable people==\n{{More citations needed section|date=June 2017}}\n* [[Arch Johnson]], stage, film, and television actor died in Snow Hill in 1997.\n* [[Judy Johnson]], was a player in the Negro Baseball Leagues and later a scout in the major leagues.  In 1975, Johnson was inducted into the [[Baseball Hall of Fame]].  He was born William Julius \"Judy\" Johnson in Snow Hill on October 26, 1900.\n* [[Sherron Mills]], professional basketball player, 1971-2016\n* [[John Walter Smith]], Congressman for [[Maryland's 1st congressional district|Maryland 1st District]], 1899\u20131900; 44th Governor of Maryland, 1900\u20131904; U.S. Senator, 1907-1919.  Born in Snow Hill on Feb 5, 1845.\n* [[Ben Tate]], NFL running back,who attended Snow Hill HS during his senior year in 2006; led team to the Maryland state championship game.\n* [[R. V. Truitt]], first lacrosse coach at the [[University of Maryland]], 1919&ndash;1927.\n* [[Ephraim King Wilson II]], U.S. Senator, 1885\u20131891; Congressman for [[United States House of Representatives, Maryland District 1|Maryland 1st District]], 1873-1874.  Born in Snow Hill on December 22, 1821.\n\n==Snow Hill in popular culture==\nIn 1999, some scenes of the [[Hollywood]] film, ''[[Runaway Bride (film)|Runaway Bride]]'' (starring [[Julia Roberts]] and [[Richard Gere]]) were shot at the [[Snow Hill High School]]. The scenes at the baseball and football games were filmed behind the school.\n\nAt the end of each episode of Adult Swim's \"Children Hospital,\" is an old advertisement for The Corddry Co Snow Hill, MD.  Seen after the final credits.  The lead actor, writer, and producer is comedian Rob Corddry, whose father is from Snow Hill. He uses the advertisement as his  production banner.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Julia A. Purnell Museum]]\n* [[Furnace Town Living Heritage Museum]]\n* [[Mt. Zion One Room School]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* {{wikivoyage-inline|Snow Hill}}\n* [http://www.snowhillmd.com/ Town of Snow Hill website]\n\n{{Geographic Location 2\n | Center    = Snow Hill\n | North     = [[Bowie, Maryland|Bowie]]<br/>[[File:US 301.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Route 301 in Maryland|US 301 North]] \n | Northeast = [[Berlin, Maryland|Berlin]]<br/>[[File:US 113.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Route 113 in Maryland|US 301 South]]\n | East      = Snow Hill Wharf<br/>[[File:MD Route 258.svg|25px]] [[Maryland Route 365|MD 365 East]]\n | ENE       = \n | Southeast = [[Chincoteague Bay]]\n | Southwest = [[Pocomoke City, Maryland|Pocomoke City]]<br/>[[File:US 113.svg|25px]] [[U.S. Route 113 in Maryland|US 301 South]]\n | South     = [[Stockton, Maryland|Stockton]], [[Chincoteague, Virginia]]<br/>[[File:MD Route 12.svg|25px]] [[Maryland Route 12|MD 12 South]]\n | WSW       =\n | West    